# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: custom-elements
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] The **`HTMLElement`** interface represents any HTML element.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Some elements directly implement this interface, while others implement it via an interface that inherits it.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string representing the access key assigned to the element.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns a string containing the element's assigned access key.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns a reference to the element's anchor element, or `null` if it doesn't have one.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A `StylePropertyMap` representing the declarations of the element's `style` attribute.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string that represents the element's capitalization behavior for user input.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Valid values are: `none`, `off`, `on`, `characters`, `words`, `sentences`.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A boolean value reflecting the `autofocus` HTML global attribute, which indicates whether the control should be focused when the page loads, or when dialog or popover become shown if specified in an element inside `<dialog>` elements or elements whose popover attribute is set.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A boolean that represents whether or not text input by a user should be automatically corrected.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This reflects the `autocorrect` HTML global attribute.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string, where a value of `true` means the element is editable and a value of `false` means it isn't.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns a `DOMStringMap` with which script can read and write the element's custom data attributes (`data-*`).
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string, reflecting the `dir` global attribute, representing the directionality of the element.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A boolean value indicating if the element can be dragged.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns the `EditContext` associated with the element, or `null` if there isn't one.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string defining what action label (or icon) to present for the enter key on virtual keyboards.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string or boolean value reflecting the value of the element's `hidden` attribute.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A boolean value indicating whether the user agent must act as though the given node is absent for the purposes of user interaction events, in-page text searches ("find in page"), and text selection.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Represents the rendered text content of a node and its descendants.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] As a getter, it approximates the text the user would get if they highlighted the contents of the element with the cursor and then copied it to the clipboard.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] As a setter, it replaces the content inside the selected element, converting any line breaks into `<br>` elements.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string value reflecting the value of the element's `inputmode` attribute.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns a boolean value indicating whether or not the content of the element can be edited.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string representing the language of an element's attributes, text, and element contents.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns the cryptographic number used once that is used by Content Security Policy to determine whether a given fetch will be allowed to proceed.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns a `double` containing the height of an element, relative to the layout.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns a `double`, the distance from this element's left border to its `offsetParent`'s left border.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] An `Element` that is the element from which all offset calculations are currently computed.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns a `double`, the distance from this element's top border to its `offsetParent`'s top border.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns a `double` containing the width of an element, relative to the layout.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] As a getter, it is the same as `HTMLElement.innerText` (it represents the rendered text content of an element and its descendants).
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] As a setter, it replaces the selected node and its contents with the given value, converting any line breaks into `<br>` elements.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Gets and sets an element's popover state via JavaScript (`"auto"`, `"hint"`, or `"manual"`), and can be used for feature detection.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Reflects the value of the `popover` global HTML attribute.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A boolean value that controls the spell-checking hint.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] It is available on all HTML elements, though it doesn't affect all of them.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A `CSSStyleDeclaration` representing the declarations of the element's `style` attribute.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A `long` representing the position of the element in the tabbing order.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string containing the text that appears in a popup box when mouse is over the element.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A boolean value representing the translation.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] A string indicating if browser-provided writing suggestions should be enabled under the scope of the element or not.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Returns an `ElementInternals` object, and enables a custom element to participate in HTML forms.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Removes keyboard focus from the currently focused element.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Sends a mouse click event to the element.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Makes the element the current keyboard focus.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Hides a popover element by removing it from the top layer and styling it with `display: none`.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Shows a popover element by adding it to the top layer and removing `display: none;` from its styles.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Toggles a popover element between the hidden and showing states.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Fired when the `value` of an `<input>`, `<select>`, or `<textarea>` element has been changed and committed by the user.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Unlike the `input` event, the `change` event is not necessarily fired for each alteration to an element's `value`.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Fires on an element that is controlled via a `button` with valid `commandForElement` and `command` values, whenever the button is interacted with (e.g., it is clicked).
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Fired when a resource failed to load, or can't be used.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Fires for elements containing a resource when the resource has successfully loaded.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This event is fired when an element or text selection is being dragged.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This event is fired when a drag operation is being ended (by releasing a mouse button or hitting the escape key).
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This event is fired when a dragged element or text selection enters a valid drop target.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This event is fired when a dragged element or text selection leaves a valid drop target.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This event is fired continuously when an element or text selection is being dragged and the mouse pointer is over a valid drop target (every 50 ms WHEN mouse is not moving ELSE much faster between 5 ms (slow movement) and 1ms (fast movement) approximately.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This firing pattern is different than `mouseover` ).
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This event is fired when the user starts dragging an element or text selection.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] This event is fired when an element or text selection is dropped on a valid drop target.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Fired on the target element of an interest invoker when interest is shown, allowing code to be run in response.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Fired on the target element of an interest invoker when interest is lost, allowing code to be run in response.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Fired when the element is a popover or `<dialog>`, before it is hidden or shown.
[src:custom-elements/api-htmlelement] Fired when the element is a popover, `<dialog>`, or `<details>` element, just after it is hidden or shown.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] The **`Window`** interface represents a window containing a DOM document; the `document` property points to the DOM document loaded in that window.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] A window for a given document can be obtained using the `document.defaultView` property.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] A global variable, `window`, representing the window in which the script is running, is exposed to JavaScript code.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] The `Window` interface is home to a variety of functions, namespaces, objects, and constructors which are not necessarily directly associated with the concept of a user interface window.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] However, the `Window` interface is a suitable place to include these items that need to be globally available.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Many of these are documented in the JavaScript Reference and the DOM Reference.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] In a tabbed browser, each tab is represented by its own `Window` object; the global `window` seen by JavaScript code running within a given tab always represents the tab in which the code is running.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] That said, even in a tabbed browser, some properties and methods still apply to the overall window that contains the tab, such as `resizeTo()` and `innerHeight`.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Generally, anything that can't reasonably pertain to a tab pertains to the window instead.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Note that properties which are objects (e.g., for overriding the prototype of built-in elements) are listed in a separate section below.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the `CacheStorage` object associated with the current context.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] This object enables functionality such as storing assets for offline use, and generating custom responses to requests.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] This property indicates whether the current window is closed or not.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the `CookieStore` object for the current document context.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a `CrashReportContext` object that enables arbitrary data to be recorded for the current top-level browsing context, which is then added to a `CrashReport` and sent to a reporting endpoint when a browser crash occurs.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a boolean that indicates whether the current document was loaded inside a credentialless `<iframe>`.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] See IFrame credentialless for more details.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a boolean value that indicates whether the website is in a cross-origin isolation state.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the `Crypto` object associated to the global object.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the `CustomElementRegistry` object, which can be used to register new custom elements and get information about previously registered custom elements.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the ratio between physical pixels and device independent pixels in the current display.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the document that the window contains.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the document Picture-in-Picture window for the current document context.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a `Fence` object instance for the current document context.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Available only to documents embedded inside a `<fencedframe>`.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the element in which the window is embedded, or null if the window is not embedded.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns an array of the subframes in the current window.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] This property indicates whether the window is displayed in full screen or not.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the history object.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Provides a mechanism for applications to asynchronously access capabilities of indexed databases; returns an `IDBFactory` object.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Gets the height of the content area of the browser window including, if rendered, the horizontal scrollbar.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Gets the width of the content area of the browser window including, if rendered, the vertical scrollbar.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a boolean indicating whether the current context is secure (`true`) or not (`false`).
[src:custom-elements/api-window] When a progressive web app (PWA) is launched with a `launch_handler` `client_mode` value of `focus-existing`, `navigate-new`, or `navigate-existing`, the `launchQueue` provides access to the `LaunchQueue` class, which allows custom launch navigation handling to be implemented for the PWA.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the number of frames in the window.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the local storage object used to store data that may only be accessed by the origin that created it.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Gets/sets the location, or current URL, of the window object.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the horizontal (X) coordinate of the top-left corner of the window's viewport, in screen coordinates.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] See `mozScreenPixelsPerCSSPixel` in `nsIDOMWindowUtils` for a conversion factor to adapt to screen pixels if needed.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the vertical (Y) coordinate of the top-left corner of the window's viewport, in screen coordinates.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] See `mozScreenPixelsPerCSSPixel` for a conversion factor to adapt to screen pixels if needed.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the current `window`'s associated `Navigation` object.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the navigator object.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the window that opened this current window.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the global object's origin, serialized as a string.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns `true` if this window belongs to an origin-keyed agent cluster.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Gets the height of the outside of the browser window.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Gets the width of the outside of the browser window.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the parent of the current window or subframe.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a `Performance` object, which includes the `timing` and `navigation` attributes, each of which is an object providing performance-related data.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] See also Using Navigation Timing for additional information and examples.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the `Scheduler` object associated with the current context.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] This is the entry point for using the Prioritized Task Scheduling API.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns a reference to the screen object associated with the window.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Both properties return the horizontal distance from the left border of the user's browser viewport to the left side of the screen.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Both properties return the vertical distance from the top border of the user's browser viewport to the top side of the screen.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] The maximum offset that the window can be scrolled to horizontally, that is the document width minus the viewport width.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] The maximum offset that the window can be scrolled to vertically (i.e., the document height minus the viewport height).
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the number of pixels that the document has already been scrolled horizontally.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns the number of pixels that the document has already been scrolled vertically.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Returns an object reference to the window object itself.
