[src:custom-elements/api-window] Releases the window from trapping events of a specific type.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Lets a website or app gain access to a sandboxed file system for its own use.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Executes a function after the browser has finished other heavy tasks.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Kept for backward compatibility with Netscape 4.x.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Transforms a `WebKitPoint` from the node's coordinate system to the page's coordinate system.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Transforms a `WebKitPoint` from the page's coordinate system to the node's coordinate system.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] In addition to the events listed below, many events can bubble from the `Document` contained in the window object.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] For example, if a script has an execution error or an image can't be found or is invalid.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired at the global scope object when the user's preferred language changes.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a storage area (`localStorage` or `sessionStorage`) has been modified in the context of another document.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the browser has lost access to the network and the value of `navigator.onLine` has switched to `false`.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the browser has gained access to the network and the value of `navigator.onLine` has switched to `true`.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired at a regular interval, indicating the amount of physical force of acceleration the device is receiving and the rate of rotation, if available.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when fresh data is available from the magnetometer orientation sensor about the current orientation of the device as compared to the Earth coordinate frame.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when fresh data is available from the magnetometer orientation sensor about the current absolute orientation of the device as compared to the Earth coordinate frame.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the browser detects that a gamepad has been connected or the first time a button/axis of the gamepad is used.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the browser detects that a gamepad has been disconnected.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the fragment identifier of the URL has changed (the part of the URL beginning with and following the `#` symbol).
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Sent when the browser hides the current document while in the process of switching to displaying in its place a different document from the session's history.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] This happens, for example, when the user clicks the Back button or when they click the Forward button to move ahead in session history.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a document is first rendered, either when loading a fresh document from the network or activating a document (either from back/forward cache (bfcache) or prerender).
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Sent when the browser makes the document visible due to navigation tasks, including not only when the page is first loaded, but also situations such as the user navigating back to the page after having navigated to another within the same tab.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a document is about to be unloaded due to a navigation.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the active history entry changes.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the window, the document and its resources are about to be unloaded.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the whole page has loaded, including all dependent resources such as stylesheets images.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the document or a child resource is being unloaded.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the browser has successfully installed a page as an application.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a user is about to be prompted to install a web application.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the window receives a message, for example from a call to `Window.postMessage()` from another browsing context.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a `Window` object receives a message that can't be deserialized.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired after the associated document has started printing or the print preview has been closed.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the associated document is about to be printed or previewed for printing.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Sent every time a JavaScript `Promise` is rejected, regardless of whether or not there is a handler in place to catch the rejection.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Sent when a JavaScript `Promise` is rejected but there is no handler in place to catch the rejection.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired on the scroll container at the end of a scrolling operation when a new scroll snap target has been selected.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired on the scroll container when the browser determines a new scroll snap target is pending, i.e., it will be selected when the current scroll gesture ends.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the orientation of the device has changed.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a display is able to be presented to.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a compatible VR device has been connected to the computer.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a compatible VR device has been disconnected from the computer.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when a display can no longer be presented to.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Fired when the presenting state of a VR device changes — i.e., goes from presenting to not presenting, or vice versa.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] Not all events that bubble can reach the `Window` object.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] To listen for events on `Window` objects, in general, you can only use the first two methods, because `Window` has no corresponding HTML element.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] However, there's a specific group of events whose listeners can be added to the `<body>` (or the deprecated `<frameset>`) element that's owned by the `Window`'s document, using the second or third methods.
[src:custom-elements/api-window] In all three cases, you see the `Window` object logged as `currentTarget`.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] The **`define()`** method of the `CustomElementRegistry` interface adds a definition for a custom element to the custom element registry, mapping its name to the constructor which will be used to create it.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] Object that controls how the element is defined.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] String specifying the name of a built-in element to extend.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] Used to create a customized built-in element.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] Thrown if the provided name is not a valid custom element name.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] Thrown if the referenced constructor is not a constructor.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] The `define()` method adds a definition for a custom element to the custom element registry, mapping its name to the constructor which will be used to create it.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] To define an autonomous custom element, you should omit the `options` parameter.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] To define a customized built-in element, you must pass the `options` parameter with its `extends` property set to the name of the built-in element that you are extending, and this must correspond to the interface that your custom element class definition inherits from.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] For example, to customize the `<p>` element, you must pass `{extends: "p"}` to `define()`, and the class definition for your element must inherit from `HTMLParagraphElement`.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] This element doesn't do anything: a real autonomous element would implement its functionality in its constructor and in the lifecycle callbacks provided by the standard.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] See Implementing a custom element in our guide to working with custom elements.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] This element extends the built-in `<p>` element.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry-define] In this minimal example the element doesn't implement any customization, so it will behave just like a normal `<p>` element.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] The **`CustomElementRegistry`** interface provides methods for registering custom elements and querying registered elements.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] To get an instance of it, use the `window.customElements` property.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] To create a scoped registry, use the `CustomElementRegistry()` constructor.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] Creates a new `CustomElementRegistry` object, for scoped usage.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] Returns the constructor for the named custom element, or `undefined` if the custom element is not defined.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] Returns the name for the already-defined custom element, or `null` if the custom element is not defined.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] Upgrades a custom element directly, even before it is connected to its shadow root.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] Associates a scoped registry with a DOM subtree, setting the custom element registry on each inclusive descendant and upgrading any custom elements.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] Returns an empty `Promise` that resolves when a custom element becomes defined with the given name.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] If such a custom element is already defined, the returned promise is immediately fulfilled.
[src:custom-elements/customelementregistry] See the Examples section in our guide to using custom elements.
[src:custom-elements/customelements] The **`customElements`** read-only property of the `Window` interface returns a reference to the global `CustomElementRegistry` object, which can be used to register new custom elements and get information about previously registered custom elements.
[src:custom-elements/customelements] The global registry is used for registering custom elements by default, but a shadow root can choose to use a scoped custom element registry in order to avoid potential clashes in defined element names.
[src:custom-elements/customelements] The most common example you'll see of this property being used is to get access to the `CustomElementRegistry.define()` method to define and register a new custom element.
[src:custom-elements/customelements] See our web-components-examples repo for more usage examples.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] One of the key features of web components is the ability to create *custom elements*: that is, HTML elements whose behavior is defined by the web developer, that extend the set of elements available in the browser.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] This article introduces custom elements, and walks through some examples.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] A custom element is implemented as a class which extends `HTMLElement` (in the case of autonomous elements) or the interface you want to customize (in the case of customized built-in elements).
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] This class will not be called by you, but will be called by the browser.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Immediately after defining the class, you should register the custom element, so you can create instances of it using standard DOM practices, such as writing the element in HTML markup, calling `document.createElement()`, etc.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] In the class constructor, you can set up initial state and default values, register event listeners and perhaps create a shadow root.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] At this point, you should not inspect the element's attributes or children, or add new attributes or children.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] See Requirements for custom element constructors and reactions for the complete set of requirements.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Once your custom element is registered, the browser will call certain methods of your class when code in the page interacts with your custom element in certain ways.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] By providing an implementation of these methods, which the specification calls *lifecycle callbacks*, you can run code in response to these events.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The position of a custom element in the DOM can be manipulated just like any regular HTML element, but there are lifecycle side-effects to consider.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Each time a custom element is moved (via methods such as `Element.moveBefore()` or `Node.insertBefore()`), the `disconnectedCallback()` and `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callbacks are fired, because the element is disconnected from and reconnected to the DOM.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] However, since these callbacks are typically used to implement any required initialization or cleanup code to run at the start or end of the element's lifecycle, running them when the element is moved (rather than removed or inserted) may cause problems with its state.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] You might for example remove some stored data that the element still needs.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] If you want to preserve the element's state, you can do so by defining a `connectedMoveCallback()` lifecycle callback inside the element class, and then using the `Element.moveBefore()` method to move the element (instead of similar methods such as `Node.insertBefore()`).
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] This causes the `connectedMoveCallback()` to run instead of `connectedCallback()` and `disconnectedCallback()`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] To make a custom element available in a page, call the `define()` method of `Window.customElements`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] This must start with a lowercase letter, contain a hyphen, and satisfy certain other rules listed in the specification's definition of a valid name.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The custom element's constructor function.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Only included for customized built-in elements, this is an object containing a single property `extends`, which is a string naming the built-in element to extend.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Once you've defined and registered a custom element, you can use it in your code.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The examples above register custom elements on the global `CustomElementRegistry` accessed via `Window.customElements`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] This means every custom element name you register must be globally unique across the entire page.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] As applications grow and begin combining components from multiple libraries, global name collisions can become a problem — if two libraries both try to define `<my-button>`, one of them will fail.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] One way to use a scoped registry is to pass it to `Element.attachShadow()` via the `customElementRegistry` option.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] You can also associate a scoped registry after the shadow root has been created by calling `initialize()`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] For declarative shadow DOM, you can use the `shadowrootcustomelementregistry` attribute on a `<template>` element.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Like built-in elements, custom elements can use HTML attributes to configure the element's behavior.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] To use attributes effectively, an element has to be able to respond to changes in an attribute's value.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is then called whenever an attribute whose name is listed in the element's `observedAttributes` property is added, modified, removed, or replaced.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Note that if the element's HTML declaration includes an observed attribute, then `attributeChangedCallback()` will be called after the attribute is initialized, when the element's declaration is parsed for the first time.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] For a complete example showing the use of `attributeChangedCallback()`, see Lifecycle callbacks in this page.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Built in HTML elements can have different *states*, such as "hover", "disabled", and "read only".
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Some of these states can be set as attributes using HTML or JavaScript, while others are internal, and cannot.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Whether external or internal, commonly these states have corresponding CSS pseudo-classes that can be used to select and style the element when it is in a particular state.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Autonomous custom elements (but not elements based on built-in elements) also allow you to define states and select against them using the `:state()` pseudo-class function.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The code below shows how this works using the example of an autonomous custom element that has an internal state `"collapsed"`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The `collapsed` state is represented as a boolean property (with setter and getter methods) that is not visible outside of the element.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] To make this state selectable in CSS the custom element first calls `HTMLElement.attachInternals()` in its constructor in order to attach an `ElementInternals` object, which in turn provides access to a `CustomStateSet` through the `ElementInternals.states` property.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The setter for the (internal) collapsed state adds the *identifier* `hidden` to the `CustomStateSet` when the state is `true`, and removes it when the state is `false`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The identifier is just a string: in this case we called it `hidden`, but we could have just as easily called it `collapsed`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] We can use the identifier added to the custom element's `CustomStateSet` (`this._internals.states`) for matching the element's custom state.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] This is matched by passing the identifier to the `:state()` pseudo-class.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] For example, below we select on the `hidden` state being true (and hence the element's `collapsed` state) using the `:hidden` selector, and remove the border.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The `:state()` pseudo-class can also be used within the `:host()` pseudo-class function to match a custom state within a custom element's shadow DOM.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Additionally, the `:state()` pseudo-class can be used after the `::part()` pseudo-element to match the shadow parts of a custom element that is in a particular state.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] There are several live examples in `CustomStateSet` showing how this works.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] In the rest of this guide we'll look at a few example custom elements.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] You can find the source for all these examples, and more, in the web-components-examples repository, and you can see them all live at https://mdn.github.io/web-components-examples/.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] First, we'll look at an autonomous custom element.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The `<popup-info>` custom element takes an image icon and a text string as attributes, and embeds the icon into the page.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] When the icon is focused, it displays the text in a pop up information box to provide further in-context information.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] To begin with, the JavaScript file defines a class called `PopupInfo`, which extends the `HTMLElement` class.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The class definition contains the `constructor()` for the class, which always starts by calling `super()` so that the correct prototype chain is established.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Inside the method `connectedCallback()`, we define all the functionality the element will have when the element is connected to the DOM.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] In this case we attach a shadow root to the custom element, use some DOM manipulation to create the element's internal shadow DOM structure — which is then attached to the shadow root — and finally attach some CSS to the shadow root to style it.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] We don't do this work in the constructor because an element's attributes are unavailable until it is connected to the DOM.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] In the above example we apply styles to the shadow DOM using a `<style>` element, but you can reference an external stylesheet from a `<link>` element instead.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] In this example we'll modify the `<popup-info>` custom element to use an external stylesheet.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] It's just like the original `<popup-info>` example, except that we link to an external stylesheet using a `<link>` element, which we add to the shadow DOM.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Note that `<link>` elements do not block paint of the shadow root, so there may be a flash of unstyled content (FOUC) while the stylesheet loads.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Many modern browsers implement an optimization for `<style>` tags either cloned from a common node or that have identical text, to allow them to share a single backing stylesheet.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] With this optimization the performance of external and internal styles should be similar.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Now let's have a look at a customized built in element example.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] This example extends the built-in `<ul>` element to support expanding and collapsing the list items.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Note that this time we extend `HTMLUListElement`, rather than `HTMLElement`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] This means that we get the default behavior of a list, and only have to implement our own customizations.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] As before, most of the code is in the `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callback.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] You use a `<ul>` element as normal, but specify the name of the custom element inside the `is` attribute.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] So far we've seen only one lifecycle callback in action: `connectedCallback()`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] In the final example, `<custom-square>`, we'll see some of the others.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The `<custom-square>` autonomous custom element draws a square whose size and color are determined by two attributes, named `"size"` and `"color"`.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The key function in this example is `updateStyle()` — this takes an element, gets its shadow root, finds its `<style>` element, and adds `width`, `height`, and `background-color` to the style.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The actual updates are all handled by the lifecycle callbacks.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is run whenever one of the element's attributes is changed in some way.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] As you can see from its parameters, it is possible to act on attributes individually, looking at their name, and old and new attribute values.
[src:custom-elements/using-custom-elements] Note that to get the `attributeChangedCallback()` callback to fire when an attribute changes, you have to observe the attributes.
